    <note>Pan(1) Jinggui [1386] Haogu's son [3692], Zonghui's [3696] grandson. His great grandfather enriched the family. Zonghui used classicist scholarship (ruxue) and the jinshi to establish this family (qijia) branch of the lineage (zu), which includes both his son, Haogu, and nephew, Haoqian [3691]. Haogu moved from Chuzhou, Songyang xian to Wuzhou, Jinhua where he was buried. Chen(1) Shu [3082], the father of Haogu's second wife, was a Huzhou, Changxing xian resident who was Liu(2) Shu(1)'s [1230] son-in-law. Chen(1) Shu's mother, Zhou(1) Shi, was also a Huzhou, Changxing xian resident. Haogu was the father-in-law of Su(2) Chi's [1491] grandson, Song [3770], and Tang(1) Situi's [8122] son, Jiang [3818]. Haogu's cousin, Haoqian, remained in Chuzhou where he was buried. The father-in-law of Jinggui's brother, Jingxian [3690], was Zhu(1) Yi [3258], a Mingzhou, Yinxian resident and author of an important biji, who was exiled to Shaozhou in the Northern Lingnan Highlands for 19 years because he did not attach himself to Qin(1) Gui [8008]. Jingxian was also the father-in-law of Zhu(1) Xi's [3257] eldest son, Shu [3263], and Lu(9) Zujian's [7055] tongnianyou. Jinggui was appointed Liangzhe yunfu in 1189 and Gongbu shilang in 1190, a post he held until at least 1192. Zhu Xi, WJ, 93.11a; Xianchun Linan zhi, 50.9a; Liangchao beiyao, 2.3a; L?Zuqian, WJ, 7.163, 8.189, 193; SHY:ZG, 71.14b; Zeng Gong, WJ, 42.4a-6a, 45.6b. CBD, 5, 3645.From Hartwell's ACTIVITY table:1166:  Dismissed (fangba) as new Taifu sicheng.1189:  Apt. LIangzhe yunfu.1190:  Apt. Gongbu shilang.1192:  In office as Gongbu shilang.</note>
